SIMPLE: perseverance
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Perseverance
<hw>Per`se*ver"ance</hw> <pr>(p⟦etil⟧r`s⟦esl⟧*v⟦emac⟧r"⟦ait⟧ns)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>pers⟦eacute⟧v⟦eacute⟧rance</ets>, L. <ets>perseverantia</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of persevering; persistence in anything undertaken; continued pursuit or prosecution of any business, or enterprise begun.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The king-becoming graces . . . <xex>perseverance</xex>, mercy, lowliness.⟦rdquo⟧  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose constant <qex>perseverance</qex> overcame⟦br⟧
Whate'er his cruel malice could invent.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Discrimination.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir J. Harrington.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Theol.)</fld> <def>Continuance in a state of grace until it is succeeded by a state of glory; sometimes called <altname>final perseverance</altname>, and <altname>the perseverance of the saints</altname>. See <er>Calvinism</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Persistence; steadfastness; constancy; steadiness; pertinacity.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1070 --></p>

<p><ent>Perseverant</ent>⟦br⟧
